{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"0f9a881d-ca5a-4faf-953b-0248b2f74e49","content":"The template.json is **functional but not fully ready** for NuGet publishing. Here's a quick audit:\n\n**✅ What's good:**\n- `identity`, `name`, `shortName`, `sourceName` are all present\n- `author` is set\n- `classifications` and `tags` look correct\n- `symbols` with a framework choice parameter is well-formed\n\n**⚠️ Issues to address:**\n\n1. **Missing `$schema`** — Add `\"$schema\": \"http://json.schemastore.org/template\"` for validation and editor support.\n2. **Missing `groupIdentity`** — Recommended for NuGet so multiple versions/variants can be grouped (e.g., `\"groupIdentity\": \"MyCompany.WebApi\"`).\n3. **Missing `precedence`** — Helps resolve conflicts when multiple template versions are installed.\n4. **No `description`** — Users won't know what this template does in `dotnet new list` output.\n5. **No template content** — The directory has no actual project files (`.csproj`, `Program.cs`, etc.) to scaffold. A template with nothing to emit is unusable.\n6. **No `.nupkg` packaging project** — You'll need a `.csproj` with `<PackageType>Template</PackageType>` and a `content/` folder containing the template to produce a NuGet package.\n\nThe biggest blocker is **#5** — there's no source project to template. After adding content, I'd prioritize adding `$schema`, `description`, and `groupIdentity` before publishing.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"9c2b87b0-992d-4081-830a-1641ea850e42","outputTokens":368,"requestId":"403F:204131:EE82374:107BD3E1:69EC1018"},"id":"0ecdc839-8065-4ac6-be07-013fc4b56808","timestamp":"2026-04-25T00:51:45.865Z","parentId":"18aa2714-17cc-46e6-9b2b-d29979e25e63"}
